arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase VII: Roman mid CE 2nd c. collapse and repairs. Aboveground canalization cut into the bedrock in the south and east. Installation of the low walls at the south ends of the East and West Walkways. Bench built along the south face of the South Corridor Wall. The floor of Room A is built up with purple sandstone bedding and low blocking wall. Room A is restructured as an animal shelter with tethering holes cut alongside the trough. Entrance to the Paradesios is blocked. A drain in the Forecourt is repaired and appointed with ceramic pipes for additional aboveground canalization.
3.00 m north south -by- 2.6 m east west.

Locus 10 is the floor of the ‘bench room.’ It is a well-laid floor made of sandstone floor pavers. The pavers are of unequal sizes, but are generally organized into roughly six rows. Some of the pavers show signs of ancient repairs, with cracks or gaps being filled in. At the end of the season, one of the pavers of this floor was lifted, to reveal a very dense subfloor (no leveling course was visible). The removed paver was approximately 9 cm thick. The floor is laid to fit the ‘bench’ feature to the east (Trench 105/106 Locus 80) and the ‘bench’ feature to the west (Locus 22). The defining walls of the 'bench room' are Locus 6 (the west wall) and Trench 105/106 Locus 58 (the east wall). The west wall abuts the walls of the octagonal vestibule room to the north, and so could not have been constructed during the original building period. As the floor of the room and the benches that line the walls are directly related to this west wall, it follows that these features would not have been constructed until Locus 6 was in place, during Stage 3. This floor, clearly an essential part of the ‘bench room,’ is phased with the rest of the room to Stage 3.
Additions to the Complex, including the small reservoir, the bathroom and the anteroom.
